Limited Access Document: To add information, please make comments. If you have questions about the document, please contact Ella Neumann at eneumann@sitkascience.org Document created using information provided by state and federal agencies, tribes, municipalities, and other organizations throughout Southeast Alaska.

GIS files, .csv files, and other information available on the SSSC Github Page: https://github.com/Sitka-Sound-Science-Center/southeast_monitoring_locations

column35: Rainfall, Soil Moisture, Groundwater Level and Soil Water Potential, Air, Soil Temperature, and Battery Voltage
column49: SP1 is about 60 cm deep with the upper 12-15 cm in dark brown, moist, silty sand with large concentration of plant roots. Below 15 cm, to bottom of hole, consists of abundant gray sandstone clasts in silty sand matrix, which ranges in color from orange-brown, brown, to gray. The SP1 sensor array consists of a water potential sensor and soil moisture sensor at 25 cm depth, a second soil moisture sensor at 50 cm depth, and a pressure transducer near bottom of hole with a port at ~55 cm depth.

column35: Rainfall, Soil Moisture, Groundwater Level and Soil Water Potential, Air, Soil Temperature, and Battery Voltage
column49: about 5 m downslope from the north rim of the drainage hollow and is 65 cm deep. The top of hard material (bedrock or till) was about 70 cm deep, but there was free water at a depth of about 50-55 cm. Material throughout the depth of the hole was moist sandy silty clay of a gelatinous consistency. Color ranged from orange-brown to dark brown. Very few stones were present. These soils were interpreted as transported/mixed, weathered volcanic ash (Jacqueline Foss, USDA Forest Service, personal communication, 2019). The SP2 sensor array consists of soil moisture sensors at 25 and 40 cm depth, and a pressure transducer lying on the bottom of the hole, with a port at about 60 cm depth.
